1
00:00:00,082 --> 00:00:17,643
Good evening.

2
00:00:18,464 --> 00:00:20,408
I trust you had a fruitful day.

3
00:00:20,428 --> 00:00:24,772
I do not say happy, but I wish that it has been happy.

4
00:00:26,001 --> 00:00:51,671
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassa

5
00:00:52,310 --> 00:00:56,395
Homage to the Buddha, blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

6
00:00:59,878 --> 00:01:04,784
Happy Easter to those of you who are still connected to Christianity.

7
00:01:08,349 --> 00:01:14,436
I thought this evening to make a bit of a meal out of that discourse that we read last night.

8
00:01:15,456 --> 00:01:17,760
It's a pun on words, of course.

9
00:01:18,516 --> 00:01:28,414
Just to center in on the first metaphor that the Buddha uses there about food, the sun's flesh, as it's called.

10
00:01:29,977 --> 00:01:35,766
He always teaches, first of all, from a sort of rational, intellectual point of view.

11
00:01:35,826 --> 00:01:39,272
Then he makes a great effort to give us a metaphor.

12
00:01:39,852 --> 00:01:43,680
So there are literally hundreds of metaphors in the scriptures.

13
00:01:44,537 --> 00:01:48,001
And he says that some people think that way.

14
00:01:48,201 --> 00:01:49,123
They understand things.

15
00:01:49,143 --> 00:01:50,444
They make a better connection.

16
00:01:51,346 --> 00:01:55,109
Most of us, of course, would use both.

17
00:01:55,290 --> 00:01:55,870
I mean, you know.

18
00:01:58,634 --> 00:02:00,415
So we were talking about the nutrients.

19
00:02:00,575 --> 00:02:03,358
I just want to read that bit again, you see.

20
00:02:04,459 --> 00:02:13,971
And then we'll talk about eating meditation, which those of you who've been here, you know, will know that it's one of my obsessive teachings.

21
00:02:14,895 --> 00:02:19,703
So, suppose a couple, so we're back in the desert.

22
00:02:19,782 --> 00:02:26,111
Suppose a couple, husband and wife, had taken limited provisions and were traveling through a desert.

23
00:02:27,014 --> 00:02:29,818
They have with them their only son, dear and beloved.

24
00:02:29,858 --> 00:02:39,671
Then in the middle of the desert, their limited provisions would be used up and exhausted, while the rest of the desert remains to be crossed.

25
00:02:40,747 --> 00:02:49,859
The husband and wife would think our limited provisions have been used up and are exhausted, while the rest of the desert remains to be crossed.

26
00:02:50,860 --> 00:02:57,487
Let us kill our only son, dear and beloved, and prepare dried and spiced meat.

27
00:02:58,509 --> 00:03:01,973
By eating our son's flesh, we can cross the rest of the desert.

28
00:03:03,094 --> 00:03:05,337
Let not all three of us perish.

29
00:03:07,528 --> 00:03:11,894
And they do that, of course, they kill and they prepare dried and roasted meat.

30
00:03:13,075 --> 00:03:16,620
So cannibalism doesn't particularly appeal to us.

31
00:03:17,159 --> 00:03:25,811
But this is a very, very strong image for telling us that hunger is one of our basic fears.

32
00:03:27,772 --> 00:03:34,700
And that when we eat, we ought to eat with the right intention, not for indulgence sake, but we'll come to that.

33
00:03:35,254 --> 00:03:36,316
None of us really.

34
00:03:36,336 --> 00:03:41,883
I mean, maybe you have, but none of us really have experienced hunger.

35
00:03:42,683 --> 00:03:47,430
We've experienced being peckish and then just going for that evening piece of toast.

36
00:03:48,352 --> 00:03:55,259
And we might have ended up a day in some peculiar situation where we haven't eaten.

37
00:03:55,881 --> 00:03:57,522
And when we get home, we're famished.

38
00:03:57,984 --> 00:04:03,591
But actually, we've never really experienced hunger, that annoying feeling.

39
00:04:03,891 --> 00:04:11,360
I certainly haven't, where you really do believe that if you don't get some food, you're dying.

40
00:04:12,401 --> 00:04:17,528
And you can see some of the gaunt faces in the refugees.

41
00:04:19,129 --> 00:04:25,478
And for me, going back to the 60s and 70s, where there were famines, in India especially.

42
00:04:27,759 --> 00:04:33,526
I've mentioned already the myth, the Greek myth of...

43
00:04:33,946 --> 00:04:40,600
who upset the goddess Demeter.

44
00:04:40,901 --> 00:04:45,490
The Roman name was Ceres, from which we get cereal.

45
00:04:45,831 --> 00:04:52,646
She was in charge of all that grows, all the stuff that people eat.

46
00:04:53,166 --> 00:04:56,269
And he went and built a banqueting hall over her shrine.

47
00:04:56,430 --> 00:04:59,853
So she cursed him with this insatiable hunger.

48
00:05:00,314 --> 00:05:06,201
And he ends up eating all the food, everybody, his own family, and finally himself.

49
00:05:07,982 --> 00:05:17,312
So this is a myth about what happens when you're actually really hungry, right?

50
00:05:19,074 --> 00:05:23,038
She cursed him with this insatiable hunger.

51
00:05:23,795 --> 00:05:32,387
Now, I did meet a man in Sri Lanka many years ago who told me that he had actually got lost out in the wilderness in the US.

52
00:05:33,288 --> 00:05:36,473
And he'd got to this stage of real hunger.

53
00:05:36,934 --> 00:05:44,745
And he said, you know, come a point where he caught a bird, a large bird, let's say a pigeon or something.

54
00:05:44,764 --> 00:05:49,110
And he actually ripped it apart and ate the raw flesh.

55
00:05:49,511 --> 00:05:52,214
So that gives you an idea of how

56
00:05:52,617 --> 00:06:03,973
And how hunger, when it gets right to the point of life or death, becomes utterly overwhelming, really.

57
00:06:04,735 --> 00:06:06,057
The same with thirst, of course.

58
00:06:07,800 --> 00:06:12,346
So I just wanted to take this opportunity, really, to...

59
00:06:13,002 --> 00:06:31,425
reintroduce some of you, because you might not have worked with me, but remind the rest of you about eating meditation and how we can use it, especially if we're off these two or three days and there's a tendency to, well, have a good meal.

60
00:06:32,607 --> 00:06:40,798
And there are three things when we're eating that we have to try and distinguish in order to liberate ourselves from indulgence.

61
00:06:41,302 --> 00:06:48,088
Now, we won't liberate ourselves from indulgence unless we see the consequences.

62
00:06:48,829 --> 00:06:52,533
And the problem is that while we're indulging ourselves, it's great.

63
00:06:52,834 --> 00:06:53,875
I mean, it's nibbana.

64
00:06:53,894 --> 00:06:54,615
What's the problem?

65
00:06:55,916 --> 00:07:02,324
But it's only afterwards that we begin to realize that there is quite a lot of suffering involved.

66
00:07:02,524 --> 00:07:09,350
And the first one, of course, is just that obsessive nature of indulgence, you know, having to have.

67
00:07:09,887 --> 00:07:16,276
We're not, I mean, just a morning cup of tea, try and give that up for a while or coffee and you'll see how obsessive it is.

68
00:07:17,416 --> 00:07:33,836
And if you look at any of your habits and you try and stop them, you'll see that there's a real strong desire coming up from that habit, which demands to be satisfied, to be gratified really is the right words of gratification.

69
00:07:35,841 --> 00:07:42,129
And the second problem would be frustration.

70
00:07:42,569 --> 00:07:45,192
Frustration always comes when you can't get what you want.

71
00:07:45,713 --> 00:07:50,899
So, you know, just look at the past week you've been in and see how many times you've been frustrated.

72
00:07:51,300 --> 00:07:54,163
Somebody's not behaved the way you wanted them to.

73
00:07:54,665 --> 00:07:57,088
A family member, somebody at work, whatever.

74
00:07:59,271 --> 00:08:01,553
Some piece of equipment hasn't worked for you.

75
00:08:01,593 --> 00:08:02,714
You're frustrated.

76
00:08:02,735 --> 00:08:04,396
The shopping didn't work.

77
00:08:04,663 --> 00:08:06,125
arrive at the right time.

78
00:08:06,586 --> 00:08:07,567
The bus was late.

79
00:08:07,608 --> 00:08:08,649
It goes on and on and on.

80
00:08:09,391 --> 00:08:10,432
And what you feel is anger.

81
00:08:10,733 --> 00:08:13,196
It's a frustration at not getting what you want.

82
00:08:14,757 --> 00:08:21,487
And, of course, once we drop all that, we just begin to establish an equanimity with the way things are.

83
00:08:21,807 --> 00:08:23,069
This is the way it is.

84
00:08:23,110 --> 00:08:28,338
That's the constant phrase we have to repeat to ourselves.

85
00:08:28,358 --> 00:08:29,418
This is the way it is.

86
00:08:29,478 --> 00:08:32,123
What's the point of getting upset?

87
00:08:32,625 --> 00:08:34,448
Grief, grief at loss.

88
00:08:34,708 --> 00:08:40,278
You know, you've only got to think if somebody actually, you know, went off with your mobile phone.

89
00:08:40,357 --> 00:08:41,239
That's a heavy grief.

90
00:08:41,278 --> 00:08:42,802
That is definitely.

91
00:08:42,822 --> 00:08:46,206
Our lives are now wrapped up in that little machine.

92
00:08:47,448 --> 00:08:54,419
But, of course, grief takes on a much deeper meaning, as we mentioned in the other day, when we lose somebody who we're attached to.

93
00:08:54,440 --> 00:09:01,029
So grief is always waiting for us when we are possessing something or something.

94
00:09:01,312 --> 00:09:04,836
At worst, identifying with ourselves.

95
00:09:06,619 --> 00:09:09,922
And then underneath all that, there is this anxiety.

96
00:09:09,961 --> 00:09:11,403
There's an anxiety of loss.

97
00:09:12,365 --> 00:09:13,765
You know, that's why we have insurance.

98
00:09:14,326 --> 00:09:15,668
Some of it's realistic, of course.

99
00:09:15,687 --> 00:09:17,711
You want to insure your house.

100
00:09:18,270 --> 00:09:26,480
I had a cousin who thought insuring your house was just a, you know, it was a, what do you call it?

101
00:09:26,500 --> 00:09:28,883
Just a trick just to get money out of you.

102
00:09:29,102 --> 00:09:31,184
So he never paid insurance for his house.

103
00:09:31,519 --> 00:09:38,289
And then, uh, there was one very, very bad storm where his roof caved in.

104
00:09:38,309 --> 00:09:51,811
Now, I don't know whether if, if, whether he made up his money, how much, you know, that roof cost him end and whether actually over the, over a long period of time, 30 odd years or so, 30 odd years, he never paid any insurance.

105
00:09:52,611 --> 00:09:56,538
Uh, he would have actually, uh, saved some money if he had paid the insurance.

106
00:09:58,100 --> 00:09:58,640
But, uh,

107
00:09:58,840 --> 00:10:11,498
You know, when we buy anything from something like, you know, like a laptop or something, they always want to give you insurance, you know, to make it last three years so you don't worry.

108
00:10:11,778 --> 00:10:16,846
See, there's your anxiety, worry at loss, worry at breakage, breaking down.

109
00:10:19,470 --> 00:10:26,620
So you can see that the more we have, the more we're in for some level of dissatisfaction, some level of suffering.

110
00:10:27,375 --> 00:10:32,101
It's all to do with this attachment, this indulgence.

111
00:10:32,121 --> 00:10:34,344
And the final one is boredom, of course.

112
00:10:34,725 --> 00:10:42,894
Boredom is when we are not getting the same excitement that we used to get from what we're indulging in.

113
00:10:44,176 --> 00:10:46,700
And that boredom is not a nice place to be.

114
00:10:46,720 --> 00:10:48,721
I mean, it's a sort of averse place.

115
00:10:49,163 --> 00:10:51,245
And there's a search for something new.

116
00:10:51,725 --> 00:10:53,488
Variety is the spice of life.

117
00:10:54,328 --> 00:10:55,490
And that's what we do.

118
00:10:55,529 --> 00:10:56,150
We chase things.

119
00:10:56,400 --> 00:11:01,846
one pleasure after another, just to keep ourselves occupied, keep ourselves happy.

120
00:11:02,225 --> 00:11:04,207
But this happiness isn't true happiness.

121
00:11:04,607 --> 00:11:15,477
As we see, it's an excitement based on over, over, wanting something more than we actually get from any object.

122
00:11:16,318 --> 00:11:25,547
And that's when we have to remind ourselves that we don't actually want the object so much as the mental state that it produces.

123
00:11:27,907 --> 00:11:39,657
So the three things that we then have to do in order to undermine all this is to distinguish between enjoying something and indulging it.

124
00:11:40,118 --> 00:11:46,383
It's not as though the Buddha is saying we shouldn't enjoy life, we shouldn't enjoy art, nature, friendship and all that sort of stuff.

125
00:11:47,144 --> 00:11:49,326
That's perfectly viable.

126
00:11:49,405 --> 00:11:56,731
He himself enjoyed, for instance, going to shrines, just the normal things of life.

127
00:11:57,707 --> 00:12:02,734
But that distinction is very difficult because indulgence is so close to enjoyment.

128
00:12:02,874 --> 00:12:09,081
I mean, aversion sort of pushes you apart from the object, but indulgence sticks you to it.

129
00:12:10,682 --> 00:12:14,486
The second thing is to begin to distinguish the body from the mind.

130
00:12:14,707 --> 00:12:27,241
And that's all to do with beginning to deconstruct our sense of self, our sense of an identity, our sense of being a whole, entire, like an integer, one number.

131
00:12:28,149 --> 00:12:35,639
And the final one, which is just as important, is to distinguish between a desire and an action.

132
00:12:36,080 --> 00:12:38,241
So we've looked at that a little bit.

133
00:12:39,163 --> 00:12:53,360
So just to go back on those, to distinguish between desire and indulgence, as I say, is difficult.

134
00:12:53,701 --> 00:12:57,245
So the way you overcome the indulgence is by putting a clear,

135
00:12:57,445 --> 00:12:58,725
intention in your mind.

136
00:12:59,226 --> 00:13:11,960
So this food, as the Buddha says, with this example of this mother and father who ate their son, you know, there has to be a real purpose for it.

137
00:13:12,921 --> 00:13:18,788
That food is something to nourish the body for the purpose of becoming liberated.

138
00:13:18,827 --> 00:13:21,090
It has that spiritual purpose to it.

139
00:13:21,559 --> 00:13:27,666
If it has any other purpose, then you have to question it as to whether it's wholesome, whether it's actually leading you on the path.

140
00:13:28,407 --> 00:13:41,801
So every time we're with a cup of tea, with that mythical biscuit, with a meal, we have to sit there for a moment and just remind ourselves, okay, this is to nourish the body, full stop, that's all.

141
00:13:42,260 --> 00:13:46,426
The fact that I enjoy it has to be received as a gift.

142
00:13:46,485 --> 00:13:49,708
You don't have to enjoy food that's nourishing.

143
00:13:49,769 --> 00:13:50,789
It can be quite...

144
00:13:51,378 --> 00:13:51,979
Tasteless.

145
00:13:53,480 --> 00:13:59,024
Porridge without sugar and all that sort of stuff.

146
00:13:59,085 --> 00:14:01,167
So that's the first thing.

147
00:14:01,206 --> 00:14:14,238
And then as you go through the meal, to begin to realize that the excitement that you had at the beginning of the meal is beginning to fade away and there's just this tasting of the food.

148
00:14:15,038 --> 00:14:21,063
So there you're beginning to distinguish the overlay of excitement that we have

149
00:14:21,432 --> 00:14:30,642
when we have a good meal in front of us, and then very slowly over, say, even as little as 10 bites or something, it becomes ordinary.

150
00:14:31,361 --> 00:14:37,528
And then that's the chance to really investigate just enjoying, just enjoying.

151
00:14:38,149 --> 00:14:46,258
And to make that clear to ourselves, we separate the body from the mind, the heart mind, from feeling, from thinking.

152
00:14:47,875 --> 00:14:55,104
And you do that by driving your attention, first of all, into the body, into the process of tasting and smelling.

153
00:14:55,924 --> 00:15:07,077
And by isolating that physical taste process, you're beginning to realize that this is just the body, right?

154
00:15:07,859 --> 00:15:12,163
It's the mind that is translating it into something beautiful.

155
00:15:12,945 --> 00:15:16,870
And when you, as it were, swallow, intending to swallow,

156
00:15:17,102 --> 00:15:18,784
And it's dropped, right?

157
00:15:19,846 --> 00:15:23,129
And you stop for a moment and you get the afterglow.

158
00:15:23,149 --> 00:15:25,150
So that afterglow is the mind.

159
00:15:25,532 --> 00:15:39,285
The mind, the heart, the feeling of well-being, the feeling of joy is our habituated reaction to the food we're eating.

160
00:15:39,525 --> 00:15:40,427
That's a habit we have.

161
00:15:41,268 --> 00:15:46,013
The habit is to become happy and to indulge, et cetera, the food we're eating.

162
00:15:46,668 --> 00:15:49,732
So it's recognizing that these are two different processes.

163
00:15:52,238 --> 00:16:00,412
And then, as I say, as the meal goes on and the excitement dies out, then one can get close to this business of just enjoyment.

164
00:16:01,293 --> 00:16:08,767
And you might find that when you're just enjoying something, there's a sense of loss because before you really enjoyed it.

165
00:16:09,107 --> 00:16:10,971
See, that's the overlay of excitement.

166
00:16:11,659 --> 00:16:16,705
And then you have to remind yourself, well, fine, I can indulge, but then I've got consequence.

167
00:16:17,225 --> 00:16:20,067
So it's, you know, it's this constant reminder.

168
00:16:20,087 --> 00:16:25,452
And eventually, of course, we find that indulgence is just too much.

169
00:16:26,052 --> 00:16:34,941
It's too much sugar, you know, and you just want to taste things as they are without overlaying excitement onto it.

170
00:16:36,543 --> 00:16:38,865
Years ago, when I was...

171
00:16:39,402 --> 00:16:55,426
teaching at the Birmingham Buddhist Vihara, there was a young man came and when he came again the next week, he said that he'd been meditating and he could no longer listen to heavy rock.

172
00:16:55,446 --> 00:17:01,274
So there you can see how refined this young fellow was becoming.

173
00:17:03,538 --> 00:17:07,063
And then the final thing, of course, is action.

174
00:17:07,532 --> 00:17:10,395
the distinction between a desire and an action.

175
00:17:11,237 --> 00:17:31,818
And so when you have your cup of tea, and I would suggest you try and do it at least once a day with a cup of tea and a biscuit or a sandwich, it doesn't matter what, you know, just sit with it, get the feel, get the hunger, feel the hunger, know that some of it is natural appetite and some of it is

176
00:17:32,086 --> 00:17:37,132
this excitement that we get from indulging, and just stay there with it for a while.

177
00:17:37,491 --> 00:17:42,877
And then feel, just feel the force of that desire of wanting to eat.

178
00:17:43,278 --> 00:17:46,742
The more hungry you are, of course, the greater that desire will be.

179
00:17:46,803 --> 00:17:50,567
And then at some point, a decision is made.

180
00:17:50,827 --> 00:17:51,587
A decision is made.

181
00:17:51,607 --> 00:17:57,315
Something, yes, you know, like you're giving permission for the desire to manifest.

182
00:17:57,335 --> 00:17:59,657
And that manifests through an act of will.

183
00:18:00,137 --> 00:18:01,619
That's your power.

184
00:18:01,869 --> 00:18:06,998
The power is to bring something from potential into actual.

185
00:18:07,478 --> 00:18:09,801
Now, the will itself is completely neutral.

186
00:18:09,862 --> 00:18:10,722
It's just a power.

187
00:18:11,423 --> 00:18:13,627
It's the intention which matters.

188
00:18:14,127 --> 00:18:16,892
It's the intention which is conditioning us.

189
00:18:17,814 --> 00:18:27,969
And it's good to make that distinction and to realize that actually you really can sit with a desire which you don't want until it fades away.

190
00:18:28,650 --> 00:18:31,354
Now, when we sit with a desire,

191
00:18:31,621 --> 00:18:39,307
which we don't want, no matter how strong it is, and wait for it to fade away completely, you get your little gift.

192
00:18:39,667 --> 00:18:44,672
The gift is one of feeling released from it, as if you've been imprisoned or shackled.

193
00:18:45,393 --> 00:18:47,734
And with that, there comes a sense of joy.

194
00:18:48,496 --> 00:18:53,941
But more than that, we're undermining that very habit that we don't want.

195
00:18:54,520 --> 00:19:00,125
And if we keep that going, eventually there comes a point where the habit just doesn't have the force over us.

196
00:19:00,460 --> 00:19:04,586
doesn't have that force and we can just see it come and let it pass.

197
00:19:05,488 --> 00:19:08,973
And that just comes by constant practice.

198
00:19:10,175 --> 00:19:17,288
If we fail, if we find ourselves chucking 10 biscuits down our throats, then it's no point in getting guilty

199
00:19:17,470 --> 00:19:19,413
or feeling horrible about that.

200
00:19:19,653 --> 00:19:37,057
You just notice that, well, just for that moment there, you gave in, but then you have to make a firm resolution, a resolute resolution that you'll be very quick to see when that desire arises and just to stay with it, suffer it.

201
00:19:37,317 --> 00:19:38,259
So you've got to suffer.

202
00:19:39,902 --> 00:19:44,488
You've got to stay with the feeling of it until it completely passes away.

203
00:19:46,089 --> 00:19:47,291
And the opposite, of course,

204
00:19:47,625 --> 00:19:52,030
If a desire comes up which you see is wholesome, then of course you empower it, right?

205
00:19:52,050 --> 00:19:55,796
Now, just in that very simple way, we can actually change ourselves.

206
00:19:56,537 --> 00:19:58,839
We are nothing but a compendium of habits.

207
00:19:58,859 --> 00:20:00,402
We're just a collection of habits.

208
00:20:00,942 --> 00:20:07,730
And it's a decision to keep some of them, develop some of them, and get rid of the ones we don't want.

209
00:20:08,412 --> 00:20:10,074
And that's just that process.

210
00:20:10,674 --> 00:20:11,756
I'm not saying it's easy.

211
00:20:11,796 --> 00:20:15,861
The stronger the habit, the more powerful

212
00:20:16,009 --> 00:20:21,778
The more established a habit, the more difficult it is to get the better of it.

213
00:20:22,720 --> 00:20:40,464
And eventually, of course, once we're fully awakened, once we're fully liberated from suffering, the traces of that habit might still appear in the heart, the heart-mind, but they just don't have any power over us at all, no?

214
00:20:44,748 --> 00:20:49,532
So I've tried to put this in a little essay, which I'll post.

215
00:20:50,012 --> 00:20:53,596
I'll post it up onto the website there.

